               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18380820-name-1070" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1070" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1070" type="surname" value="JOHNSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1070" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT JOHNSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Lion-street, Kent-road. On the 16th of August I was opposite the Horse Guards—I had a parcel in my pocket, containing sixteen sheets of paper, which belonged to Mr. Barclay Far<lb></lb>quharson Watson—this is the paper which contained them—the papers have been taken out by Mr. Watson—they were the Abstract of some property in Essex.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18380820-name-1071" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1071" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1071" type="surname" value="WEBB"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380820-name-1071" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES WEBB</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable V</hi> 134.) About three o'clock on the af<lb></lb>ternoon of the 16th of August, I was near the Horse Guards, and saw the prisoner put his hand into this gentleman's pocket, and take out his hand-kerchief part of the way—he waited about two minutes, and then took out this parcel—I took him with it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. It was dropping out of the pocket, and I took it to give it to the gentleman. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>. No, he took the handkerchief partly out, and then put it back again, because it was a cotton one—he then took this parcel from the left-hand pocket—it was not likely to fall out.</p>
